│ Hello! As a senior LLVM maintainer for `loop-vectorize`, I'd be happy to help you diagnose │
│ this issue. Crashing assertions can be tricky, but the detailed information you've         │
│ provided is an excellent starting point. Let's dive in.                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ Based on the backtrace and the reproducer, the problem lies within the logic that prepares │
│ the epilogue loop, specifically when handling multiple induction variables. The assertion  │
│ `EPResumeVal && "must have a resume value for the canonical IV"` tells us that the         │
│ vectorizer failed to compute the starting value for the canonical induction variable       │
│ (`%iv`) in the epilogue.                                                                   │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 1. Understanding the Issue                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `loop-vectorize` pass often splits a loop into three parts:                            │
│ 1.  A main vectorized loop that processes iterations in vector-sized chunks.               │
│ 2.  An optional "epilogue" loop that handles any remaining iterations if the total trip    │
│ count isn't a multiple of the vector factor.                                               │
│ 3.  A pre-header and exit logic to manage control flow.                                    │
│                                                                                            │
│ For the epilogue loop to work correctly, it needs to know where to "resume" execution. For │
│ an induction variable, this "resume value" is its value after the main vectorized loop has │
│ completed. The failing assertion indicates that this resume value for the canonical        │
│ induction variable (`%iv`) was never calculated and stored.                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log                                                               │
│                                                                                            │
│ The `opt` log shows that Scalar Evolution (SCEV) correctly analyzes both induction         │
│ variables:                                                                                 │
│ -   `%iv`: A standard canonical induction variable `{0,+,1}`.                              │
│ -   `%iv.2`: A non-standard induction variable `{0,+,-16777216}`.                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The key observation is that the value used outside the loop, `%res`, is derived from       │
│ `%iv.2`, not the canonical `%iv`. This is a crucial detail. The vectorizer's logic for     │
│ deciding which induction variables need epilogue resume values is based on whether they    │
│ are used outside the loop (i.e., are "live-out").                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 3. Root Cause Analysis                                                                 │
│                                                                                            │
│ The root cause lies in `LoopVectorizePass::createEpilogueSCEV`, the function responsible   │
│ for calculating these resume values. This function iterates through all induction          │
│ variables and computes their value at the end of the main vector loop. However, it         │
│ contains a flawed optimization:                                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp                                         │
│ // In LoopVectorizePass::createEpilogueSCEV                                                │
│ for (auto *Ind : Inductions) {                                                             │
│   // No need to compute the resume value for induction variables that are not              │
│   // used outside the loop.                                                                │
│   if (!isUsedOutsideOfLoop(Ind->getInduction(), L))                                        │
│     continue;                                                                              │
│   // ...                                                                                   │
│ }                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ This code skips the calculation for any induction variable that is not used outside the    │
│ loop. In our reproducer:                                                                   │
│ -   The canonical IV `%iv` is only used for the loop's exit condition. It is **not** used  │
│ after the loop.                                                                            │
│ -   The other IV, `%iv.2`, is used to compute `%res`, which is returned from the function. │
│ It **is** used after the loop.                                                             │
│                                                                                            │
│ Because `%iv` is not live-out, `createEpilogueSCEV` skips it, and no resume value is added │
│ to the `SCEV2Value` map for it.                                                            │
│                                                                                            │
│ Later, when `preparePlanForEpilogueVectorLoop` is called, it unconditionally expects a     │
│ resume value for the canonical IV, as it's fundamental to constructing the epilogue loop's │
│ structure. It looks up this value and finds nothing, triggering the assertion.             │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to recognize that the canonical IV's resume value is *always* needed for the    │
│ epilogue, regardless of whether it's used outside the loop. We must remove the             │
│ `isUsedOutsideOfLoop` check for the canonical IV.                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│ The fix is to modify `LoopVectorizePass::createEpilogueSCEV` to ensure it always computes  │
│ the resume value for the canonical induction variable.                                     │
│                                                                                            │
│ **File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp`                                │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // Edit at line 9758                                                                       │
│ for (auto *Ind : Inductions) {                                                             │
│   // No need to compute the resume value for induction variables that are not              │
│   // used outside the loop.                                                                │
│   if (!isUsedOutsideOfLoop(Ind->getInduction(), L))                                        │
│     continue;                                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│   // ...                                                                                   │
│ }                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ **Proposed Change**:                                                                       │
│                                                                                            │
│ ```cpp                                                                                     │
│ // Edit at line 9758                                                                       │
│ for (auto *Ind : Inductions) {                                                             │
│   // No need to compute the resume value for induction variables that are not              │
│   // used outside the loop, unless it is the canonical IV.                                 │
│   if (Ind->getInduction() != L->getCanonicalInductionVariable() &&                         │
│       !isUsedOutsideOfLoop(Ind->getInduction(), L))                                        │
│     continue;                                                                              │
│                                                                                            │
│   // ...                                                                                   │
│ }                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                        │
│                                                                                            │
│ This change adds an exception to the check: if the induction variable `Ind` is the         │
│ canonical IV, its resume value will be computed even if it's not used outside the loop.    │
│                                                                                            │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                                                          │
│                                                                                            │
│ The crash was caused by an overly aggressive optimization that skipped the calculation of  │
│ the epilogue resume value for the canonical induction variable when it wasn't live-out.    │
│ However, this value is essential for constructing the epilogue itself. The proposed edit   │
│ corrects this logic by ensuring the canonical IV's resume value is always computed,        │
│ thereby fixing the assertion failure and allowing the vectorizer to proceed correctly.     │
│                                                                                            │
│ I'll go ahead and prepare the patch for review. Thanks for bringing this to my attention!  │
